STEAMED RICE PAPER DUMPLINGS (GF / DF) âœ¨ My second most popular recipe of 2025 with 4.8M views! This was one of my favorite recipes this year and Iâ€™m so glad so many of you enjoyed it as well. That sauceeee is so good itâ€™s drinkable and the dumpling filling is packed with so much flavor I could eat 100 of â€˜em. Save and follow @caitlinjesson for easy gluten free and dairy free recipes. 1 lb peeled and deveined shrimp, tails removed and minced 3 tbsp fresh ginger, peeled and minced 4 cloves garlic, minced Â¼ cup chives, finely chopped 2 tsp low sodium tamari 1 tbsp arrowroot or cornstarch Pinch of black pepper 15-20 sheets of rice paper Sauce: 2 tbsp chili crisp â…“ cup rice vinegar â…“ cup low sodium tamari 2 cloves garlic, grated 1 tbsp coconut sugar 4 green onions, finely chopped Â¼ cup cilantro, finely chopped Â¼ cup avocado oil To make sauce, combine ingredients in a medium sized bowl and whisk until combined. To make dumpling filling, add shrimp, ginger, garlic, chives, soy sauce, arrowroot and pepper to a bowl and mix well. Fill a large bowl with water then generously wet a cutting board and set it next to your bowl. Line a steaming basket or a plate with parchment paper and spray with nonstick spray. Dip a piece of rice paper into your water bowl. Allow it to soak for 5-10 seconds until it begins to soften slightly. At the rice paper to your cutting board then fold all four of the edges in to form a square. Add 1 heaping tbsp of filling to the center of the rice paper square then fold all of the corners in towards the center and press them together to seal the filling in the dumpling. Transfer dumpling to steaming basket and repeat with remaining dumplings. You will need to steam in two batches. If using a steaming basket, bring 2 inches of water to a boil in a large pot then place steaming basket on top and steam for 10 minutes. If using a plate, bring 2 inches of water to a boil in a large pot. Add a heat safe bowl to the water upside down then set the plate on top of the bowl. Cover and steam for 10 minutes. Serve with dipping sauce.

Did you know you can see underwater without goggles using just your hands? Navy SEALs and other combat divers use this clever trick in emergencies. By cupping their hands over their eyes and creating a tiny air bubble, they form a mini â€œgoggleâ€ that lets light pass correctly into the eyes, temporarily restoring clear vision. Normally, water bends light differently than air, which makes everything look blurry. The air bubble corrects this refraction, letting the eyes focus properly for a short time. ğŸ“ This is not something I do often, just an occasional reset for utensils that get heavy use or hold onto odors (garlic, onion, oils). The Disney scenes you grew up watching were secretly reused from other films. ğŸ‘€ For decades, Disney quietly reused entire animation sequences across its classic films, not as a shortcut, but as a survival strategy. During the 1950s through the 1970s, animation was one of the most expensive art forms in the world. Every frame had to be drawn by hand, and studios were under immense pressure to produce feature-length films on tight budgets. To save time and money without sacrificing quality, Disney artists used a process called â€œrotoscoping.â€ They traced over existing animation frames from earlier movies to preserve lifelike motion, fluidity, and emotion while reducing thousands of hours of labor. You can see it clearly in scenes from The Jungle Book, Robin Hood, and The Aristocats, identical movements repurposed and re-imagined with new characters and settings. What began as an economic necessity ended up shaping Disneyâ€™s visual identity. Those familiar gestures, dances, and smiles became part of the studioâ€™s DNA, small echoes of creativity that still connect generations today. Love Technology? The Rubensâ€™ tube is a physics device invented in 1904 by Heinrich Rubens. It shows how sound waves move by using flames. The tube is filled with gas and has many small holes along the top. When sound is played into one end of the tube, the pressure inside changes, and the flames rise and fall in patterns that match the sound waves. This turns invisible sound vibrations into something you can actually see. Low notes create slow, smooth waves, while higher notes make tighter, faster patterns. Musicians and science teachers often use the Rubensâ€™ tube because itâ€™s a dramatic and visual way to show how sound works. Itâ€™s a great example of science and art coming together, turning music into moving flames.

This is Bloomframe window, first unveiled by Dutch architect HofmanDujardin. At the touch of a button or a gentle push the frame opens outward, creating a floored balcony complete with railings. It was created as a solution for dense urban housing, letting residents enjoy fresh air and views without the need for major construction. Today, variations of the concept are being installed in modern buildings across Europe and beyond. Extra Fact: The Bloomframe window won multiple international design awards and has even been showcased as a future forward idea for compact living in major cities like New York and Tokyo. #architecture #designinnovation #engineering #modernliving #citylife #architecturelovers #urbanliving #futuristicdesign #interiordesign #smartliving #constructiontech #housingdesign #innovation #cityarchitecture #creativeengineering #homedesign #designgoals #urbanarchitecture #compactliving #archilovers

Ingredients: 1 pound ground pork 2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger 2 teaspoons minced fresh garlic 5 green onions, thinly sliced, divided 1/4 cup chopped cilantro, divided 3 cups tri-color slaw mix, divided 1/3 cup soy sauce, divided 1 tablespoon sesame oil 1/4 teaspoon kosher salt 1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper 10 (4 inch) mini flour tortillas 2 tablespoons avocado or canola oil, plus more as needed 2 teaspoons rice vinegar 2 1/2 teaspoons white sugar 1 1/2 tablespoons water 2 teaspoons Sriracha or other hot sauce Directions Add pork, ginger, garlic, 1/2 of the green onions, 2 tablespoons cilantro, 1 cup slaw mix, 1 1/2 Tablespoons soy sauce, sesame oil, salt and pepper to a bowl and mix until combined. Spread pork mixture in a thin layer all the way to the edges of each tortilla and set aside. Combine remaining soy sauce with vinegar, sugar, water and hot sauce in a small bowl and whisk until sugar is dissolved. Set aside. Working in batches in a large skillet or griddle, heat 1 tablespoon oil over medium-high heat. Place tortillas, meat side down in the hot pan and cook, undisturbed, until browned and mostly cooked through, about 3 minutes. Flip and cook until browned and lightly toasted, another 1 to 2 minutes. Flip once more and cook 30 seconds. Remove from pan and repeat with remaining tortillas. Top tacos evenly with remaining green onion, cilantro, and slaw mix. Serve drizzled with sauce or serve sauce on the side for dipping. ğŸ§‘â€ğŸ³: @nicolemcmom #tacos #smashedtaco #easydinners #dinnerideas #dinner

ğŸ˜‚ Breaking Bad is an acclaimed American television series created by Vince Gilligan that originally aired from 2008 to 2013. The story follows Walter White, a high school chemistry teacher in Albuquerque, New Mexico, who turns to manufacturing methamphetamine after being diagnosed with terminal lung cancer. In an effort to secure his familyâ€™s financial future, he partners with a former student, Jesse Pinkman, and becomes increasingly entangled in the criminal underworld. The show is celebrated for its intense storytelling, moral complexity, and the gradual transformation of Walter from a sympathetic figure into a feared drug kingpin. The series received widespread critical acclaim for its writing, acting, and character development, particularly the performances of Bryan Cranston as Walter White and Aaron Paul as Jesse Pinkman. Over its five-season run, *Breaking Bad* garnered numerous awards, including 16 Primetime Emmy Awards. It is frequently cited as one of the greatest television shows of all time for its innovative narrative structure and deep exploration of themes like identity, power, and consequence. Its legacy was further expanded with the prequel series *Better Call Saul* and the follow-up film *El Camino: A Breaking Bad Movie*.

People with celiac disease can kiss without fear, even if their partner has just eaten gluten, according to a new study. People with celiac disease have an immune response to gluten, a protein found in foods such as bread, pasta, gummy bears and soy sauce. Everyday activities often require careful calculation to avoid exposure. With no official guidance, health care providers have been left to offer their best judgment when advising patients on whether itâ€™s safe to kiss someone who just ate gluten. Anne Lee, an assistant professor of nutritional medicine at the Celiac Disease Center at Columbia University in New York City, decided to change that. The study included 10 couples that all had one partner with celiac disease and one who didn't have it. They wanted to see whether kissing the partner who had eaten gluten would trigger symptoms in the celiac partner. Lee and her team tested this using two scenarios. Both started with the non-celiac partner eating 10 saltine crackers before kissing their gluten-free partners. In one instance, the couples waited five minutes before going in for a smooch. In another, the gluten-eating partner drank half a glass of water before the kiss. Read more at the link in bio.

Anton Kreil, a former Goldman Sachs trader, challenges the conventional wisdom that homeownership is a guaranteed path to financial security. He contends that mortgages, often perceived as assets, are substantial liabilities that can impede financial freedom. Kreil points out that the financial industry promotes homeownership as a prudent investment, yet this perspective overlooks the long-term debt burden it imposes. Beyond the principal loan amount, homeowners face significant interest payments, maintenance expenses, property taxes, and potential opportunity costs. These cumulative costs can surpass the propertyâ€™s appreciation, leading to a net financial loss over time. For instance, a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage at 4% interest on a $300,000 home results in approximately $215,000 paid in interest alone over the loanâ€™s duration. When adding maintenance costsâ€”averaging 1% of the homeâ€™s value annuallyâ€”property taxes, and insurance, the total expenditure can substantially exceed the homeâ€™s market value appreciation. She is the cutest! Children have a way of speaking the truth with such honesty - it can be refreshing, even if it catches us off guard. Their words often come without filters, reflecting what they genuinely see, think, and feel. It reminds us that there is beauty in saying things simply as they are, without overthinking. I find it interesting how differently we experience social settings. Personality types can vary - some people are true introverts who feel comfortable in solitude, while others are pure extroverts who gain energy from social time. Then there are those in between: ambiverts who balance both, and introverted extroverts and extroverted introverts who shift between needing social connection and quiet time. I believe recognizing these differences can help us, as parents, understand and respect our childrenâ€™s natural rhythms, supporting them in finding balance and comfort in both new and familiar places. The Modern Workplace Challenge In todayâ€™s fast-paced work environment, the ability to multitask is often seen as a valuable skill. Many employers expect their employees to juggle multiple tasks simultaneously, believing that this approach enhances productivity and efficiency. However, the reality for many workers is that focusing on one task at a time can lead to higher quality work and greater overall satisfaction. This description explores the challenges and benefits of both multitasking and single-tasking in the modern workplace, offering insights into how to navigate these expectations effectively. The Pressure to Multitask Employer Expectations In many industries, employers prioritize multitasking as a key competency. They believe that employees who can handle several tasks at once are more efficient and can accomplish more in less time. This expectation can create significant pressure on employees to constantly switch between tasks, leading to a stressful work environment. The Illusion of Efficiency While multitasking might seem efficient, numerous studies have shown that it can actually reduce productivity. Constantly switching between tasks can lead to cognitive overload, increased errors, and lower overall quality of work. Despite these findings, the myth of multitasking efficiency persists in many workplaces. The Benefits of Single-Tasking Improved Focus and Quality Single-tasking, or focusing on one task at a time, allows for deeper concentration and higher quality output. When employees can dedicate their full attention to a single task, they are more likely to produce work that is accurate, thorough, and well-considered. This approach minimizes mistakes and enhances overall performance. Reduced Stress and Burnout Focusing on one task at a time can significantly reduce stress levels and prevent burnout. Multitasking often leads to feelings of being overwhelmed and constantly rushed. In contrast, single-tasking provides a sense of control and accomplishment, as employees can complete tasks fully before moving on to the next.

Safe to say these Greek-Style Smash Burgers have changed my life. @chilesandsmoke made this method viral and instead of the classic burger take (which is made with a tortilla and burger sauce- YUM!), I decided to make lamb burgers and do them Greek-style! Tastes like the best Gyro Iâ€™ve ever had. Theyâ€™re perfect for a backyard BBQ or just a fun weeknight dinner. Enjoy! Ingredients: 1 lb ground lamb or beef 1/2 red onion, finely minced or grated 3 cloves garlic, minced 2 tbsp fresh mint 1 tsp kosher salt 1/2 tsp black pepper 1/2 tsp dried oregano 1/2 tsp paprika Pita bread Toppings: lettuce, tomato, cucumber, red onion, feta cheese, zaâ€™atar Tzatziki: 3/4 cup Greek yogurt 1/2 cucumber, grated 1 clove garlic, minced Juice from 1 lemon 2 tbsp fresh dill, chopped 2 tbsp fresh mint, chopped 1 tbsp olive oil 1 tsp kosher salt, plus more to taste Instructions: Grate the cucumber on the large holes of a box grater. QUINOA WRAP PLANT PROTEIN SERIES PROTEIN PER SERVING: 29gr INGREDIENTS (makes 4-5 wraps / 2 servings) 100gr quinoa 160ml water + extra for soaking FILLING 200gr tempeh, crumbled 6 Tbsp light soy sauce 4 Tbsp maple syrup 2 Tbsp tomato paste 1 tsp smoked paprika 1 tsp liquid smoke (optional) sesame oil to cook Small handful of spinach 100gr high protein yogurt Juice of 1/2 lemon 1 Tbsp runny tahini METHOD WRAPS Cover the quinoa with water and let soak overnight Drain the quinoa and rinse well. In a blender, combine the quinoa and 160ml water. Adjust seasoning as needed. Blend until smooth. Heat a non-stick pan over low heat. If itâ€™s not non-stick, grease it lightly. Once hot, pour the equivalent of one ladleful of batter onto the pan and spread it thinly using the bottom of the ladle. Wait for bubbles to form on the surface and the edges to crisp (around 1-1.5 minutes), then gently flip the wrap. Cook for another minute. Repeat until all the batter is used. FILLING In a container, whisk together soy sauce, maple syrup, tomato paste, smoked paprika, and liquid smoke. Add the crumbled tempeh and stir to combine. Heat sesame oil in a non-stick pan. Once hot, add the tempeh and pan-fry for 10-12 minutes. Set aside to cool slightly. In a small bowl, whisk together yogurt,tahini and lemon juice. ASSEMBLY Spread a generous tablespoon of yogurt dressing onto the centre of each wrap. Add a small handful of spinach, a spoonful of tempeh, and a drizzle of yogurt dressing. Enjoy! If youâ€™re using a different brand to mine the nutritional facts may vary slightly :)Macros x serving: Kcal 438| 48C - 14F - 29P #highproteinmeals #highproteindiet #wraps #plantbased #plantbasedmeal

COTTAGE CHEESE TACOS ğŸŒ®ğŸ¥‘ You can now find the full recipe on my website!! (In bio) or search Foodieholly.com I have been seeing the cottage cheese wrap trend all over my feed recently and I had to make my own twist with these little breakfast tacos and they turned out so good! High protein and delicious ğŸ˜‹ INGREDIENTS - 3-4 tbsp cottage cheese (I used low fat) - 1 egg white - pepper, oregano & chilli flakes Topping - 2 eggs - 2 tbsp pesto - Handful rocket - chopped chives - Sriracha METHOD - To a bowl whisk the cottage cheese and egg white together with a fork - To a baking sheet spoon the cottage cheese into two equal circles and season with salt, pepper and chilli flakes - Bake in the oven at 200 degrees Celsius for 25 minutes (oven times may differ so keep an eye on them until they look crispy) take out half way and dab excess liquid with a paper towel and use a spatula to push back into shape - Once done, leave to cool for 10 minutes and prepare toppings - assemble tacos with the pesto, two eggs, sriracha, chives and enjoy! #recipe #easyrecipe #recipeshare #ukfoodblogger #ukfoodie #recipeoftheday

Roasted Cauliflower, Chickpea & Kale Salad ğŸ¥¬I have been making different variations of this for years because itâ€™s such a great combination and perfect to get in lots of goodnessâœ¨And I promise, even if you are not a kale lover you are going to absolutely love this one ğŸ˜‰ğŸ‘‡ğŸ» Serves 2 Ingredients: 1/2 head of cauliflower - cut into florets 1 can (400g) chickpeas - drained and rinsed 1/2 tbsp garlic powder 1/2 tbsp smoked paprika 1/2 tbsp maple syrup a generous drizzle of olive oil for roasting salt & pepper to taste 2 handfuls of kale - stems removed and chopped really finely a bunch of coriander (about 20g) - chopped 2 spring onions - finely chopped 1/2 avocado - chopped a handful of toasted pumpkin seeds For the dressing: 3 tbsp extra virgin olive oil the juice of 1/2 lemon 1 tsp wholegrain mustard 1 tsp maple syrup salt & pepper to taste Add the cauliflower and chickpeas to a large baking tray and drizzle with the olive oil, garlic powder, smoked paprika, maple syrup, olive oil, salt and pepper. Toss everything really well and roast in the oven at 200 degrees Celsius for 30-35 minutes until the chickpeas are crispy and the cauliflower is charred. In the meantime add the kale together with a pinch of salt to a large bowl. Using your hands massage the kale until it starts to wilt. Make the dressing by mixing all the ingredients together. Add the roasted chickpeas and cauliflower to the bowl with the kale together with the coriander and spring onions. Pour the dressing over and mix well. Serve with the chopped avocado and toasted pumpkin seeds.

Introducing the Locomotion Anamorphic Cup & Saucer: A masterpiece by @luycho showcasing a fusion of barrier grid animation and anamorphic projection on fine porcelain. The saucer's distorted imagery is ingeniously reconstructed through reflection off the cup's surface, while the gold mirroring consists of parallel lines selectively reflecting elements of the pattern. Fun fact: This technique originated in the Renaissance era, where artists experimented with anamorphosis to create illusions of depth and movement in their works. Rotating the cup (or the saucer and cup together) unveils an enchanting scene of a soaring bird or galloping horse, captivating viewers with its dynamic motion and intricate design. Video: @physicsfun

THE BEST GLUTEN FREE BREAD RECIPE ğŸ¥° The Best Gluten Free Rolls (herbs are optional but add so much flavor) Ingredients - 1Â¼ cups dairy-free milk (I used almond) - 2 tbsp vegan butter - 1 packet yeast (7g) - 1Â½ tbsp sugar - 1 cup tapioca flour (130g) - Â¾ cup brown or white rice flour (102g) - Â¾ cup potato starch (90g) - 2 tsp baking powder - 2 tsp xanthan gum (substitutes: 4 tsp psyllium husk powder or 4 tsp unflavored gelatin powder) - 2 tsp salt - 1.5 tbsp each: fresh rosemary, thyme & sage - 1 tbsp olive oil - 2 eggs Instructions 1. In a microwavable measuring cup, combine dairy-free milk and vegan butter. Microwave for 1 minute and 10 seconds. 2. In a large mixing bowl, combine gluten-free yeast and sugar. Whisk in your heated milk mixture. Set aside while this proofs for 10 minutes. 3. In a small mixing bowl, combine brown rice flour, potato starch, tapioca flower, xanthan gum, salt, baking powder and herbs. 4. Once yeast is proofed, mix in eggs and olive oil. Slowly add in flour mixture and beat until well combined. 5. Coat your muffin tin with coconut iil spray, or use butter/oil you have on hand. Spoon dough into muffin cups, Â¾ full. Wet your finger tips and gently smooth the top of each. 6. Dip scissors in tapioca flour and snip the dough in each cup in half, then snip in half again so you end up with quarters. Cover muffin tin with foil and refrigerate for at least 8 hours (24 hours max). 8. Baking time! Take your muffin tin out of the fridge and place on counter while your oven preheats to 350 degrees. Bake for 30-34 minutes until tops are deep golden brown. Enjoy ğŸ¥¹ Inspo: @yeswehackrice gluten-free bakery in Shibuya City, Tokyo, Japan ğŸ‡¯ğŸ‡µâ¤ï¸ Recipe adapted from the wonderful Rachel, recreatinghappiness.com âœ¨

Balsamic Mediterranean salad recipe Ingredients - 1 bag of Persian cucumbers - 1 red onion - 3 multicolor bell peppers - 1 head of parsley - 2 avocado - 2 cans of rinsed and drained chickpeas - 1/2 a cup olive oil - Juice of two lemons - 1/4 cup balsamic vinegar - 1 tbs oregano - Big pinch of red pepper flakes - 1 tbs cumin - 1 tbs sea salt Instructions 1. Dice your cucumbers and add them to a big salad bowl. 2. Mince your red onion and add it to the bowl. 3. Cut the ends off, core, and chop your bell peppers, add them. 4. Finely mince your parsley and add it. 5. Cube your avocado and add them (optional) 6. Add your chickpeas, olive oil, lemon juice, oregano, red pepper flakes, cumin, and salt. 7. Toss everything together and enjoy! #healthy #glutenfree #dairyfree #mediteranneanfood

Link in our profile to check them out â˜ï¸ Hereâ€™s how to make these homemade cheez its (printable recipe is on our site, link in bio!) 8 ounces sharp cheddar cheese, shredded 1 cup all purpose flour 1/2 tsp salt, plus more for topping 1/4 cup unsalted butter, cubed 2 tablespoons whole milk (cold) Preheat oven to 325ËšF and line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper. Add the cheese, flour and salt to a food processor and pulse several times. Add in the butter and pulse a few more times, until the dough is crumbly. Add in the milk, then pulse several more times. The dough wonâ€™t come together in a ball, but it should come together when you press it between two fingers. Transfer to a lightly floured surface. Roll into a large rectangle, rolling as thinly as possible. We go even thinner than 1/8-inch as they puff up quite a bit when baking. Using a knife, pizza cutter or fluted pastry wheel, slice into 1-inch squares. Use the flat end of a skewer to poke a hole all the way through each cracker. Transfer to sheet pans and sprinkle with more salt. Bake for 17-20 minutes, until deep golden brown on the bottom of each cracker. If they are too light, they wonâ€™t have much crisp. Let cool completely before enjoying! Questions? Let us know in the comments below!
